---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base
  title="Legal"
  description="Orogen legal disclaimers: OROG is a work token, not a security. USEFUL was a working name (now OROG). Howey defence via Inc./Foundation split. US retail geo-fence at TGE. EU AI Act stance. HIPAA/PCI compliance scope."
  path="/legal"
>
  <section class="container-page py-16">
    <p class="heading-eyebrow">Legal</p>
    <h1 class="mt-2 text-4xl font-semibold tracking-tight sm:text-5xl">Disclaimers, scope, and posture.</h1>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-crust-300">
      This page reflects the protocol's regulatory posture as of the current
      snapshot. It is not legal advice. Customers operating in regulated
      industries should consult counsel on the applicability of Orogen to their
      use case. The foundation's contact for legal queries is
      <a href="mailto:legal@orogen.network">legal@orogen.network</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="container-narrow space-y-10 pb-20">
    <div>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight">1. Token status</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-crust-300">
        OROG is the work token of the Orogen network. The four uses are
        (a) gateway burn on customer top-up, (b) operator stake, (c) validator
        stake, (d) governance. The protocol does not advertise, encourage, or
        accommodate purchase of OROG for the purpose of holding it for price
        appreciation. The site does not use the words "APY", "earn", "yield",
        or "passive income" anywhere by design.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-3 text-crust-300">
        This is not a securities offering. The token launches via TGE only after
        the network has sustained $1M annualized revenue on the centralised
        stack and the Day-1 burn loop is operational. The marketing path is
        explicitly utility-first: the token is the medium of exchange for
        compute, not an investment instrument.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight">2. USEFUL was the working name</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-crust-300">
        Earlier internal drafts used "USEFUL" as the token ticker. The
        production name is OROG (4 chars), and the network is Orogen
        (<code class="rounded bg-crust-800 px-1 py-0.5">orogen.network</code>). The rename is reflected in
        all public materials. RFC-0007's
        <code class="rounded bg-crust-800 px-1 py-0.5">useful_nonce</code>
        field name is preserved for backwards compatibility with the
        on-chain commitment schema.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight">3. Howey-test posture</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-crust-300">
        The foundation operates a two-entity structure designed to position
        OROG as a utility token under US regulatory analysis:
      </p>
      <ul class="mt-3 list-disc space-y-2 pl-6 text-crust-300">
        <li>
          <strong class="text-crust-100">Orogen Inc.</strong> — a for-profit
          entity (Delaware C-corp) that operates the
          centralised gateway, employs the core engineering team, and provides
          commercial support contracts to enterprise customers. Inc. does not
          hold the foundation's token allocation.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong class="text-crust-100">Orogen Foundation</strong> — a
          non-profit Swiss Stiftung (Zug) that holds the treasury, runs governance
          tooling, funds ecosystem grants, and operates the dispute panel.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p class="mt-3 text-crust-300">
        The split is intended to support the Howey factor of "no common
        enterprise dependent on the efforts of others" by ensuring no single
        entity's promotional efforts are required for token utility — the BME
        loop is mechanical and the validator network is permissionless from
        Q3 2027 onward.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight">4. US retail geo-fence at TGE</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-crust-300">
        At TGE, the gateway and the AMM enforce a geo-fence excluding US
        natural-person retail participants from primary token acquisition until
        a regulatory pathway is established. US-based enterprise customers can
        consume inference services via the gateway (paying USDC/USD) without
        directly holding OROG — the burn happens at the gateway layer. US-based
        operators can participate by registering as legal entities and entering
        into a per-tier compute services agreement.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-3 text-crust-300">
        The geo-fence is reviewed quarterly. Lifting it requires (a) a
        no-action letter or equivalent regulatory clarity in the US, or
        (b) a registration path appropriate to the network's posture.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight">5. EU AI Act</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-crust-300">
        The EU AI Act applies to providers of general-purpose AI models and to
        deployers of high-risk AI systems. Orogen, in its role as a compute
        substrate, does not train or fine-tune base models; it serves inference
        of customer-selected models. The foundation publishes a model-card
        transparency notice per base model registered via pallet-model-registry
        and supports customer-side disclosure of which (base_model, adapter)
        served a given request via the response receipt. Customers deploying
        high-risk AI systems remain responsible for their own AI Act
        compliance.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight">6. HIPAA, PCI, SOC 2 scope</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-crust-300">
        Orogen does not claim HIPAA compliance, PCI compliance, or SOC 2
        certification at launch. The TEE-anchored verification stack provides
        strong technical guarantees against host-OS or cloud-provider access to
        plaintext prompts and responses, but technical posture is not the
        same as regulatory certification. Customers requiring formal
        compliance certifications should contact
        <a href="mailto:enterprise@orogen.network">enterprise@orogen.network</a>
        to discuss compliance-tier scoping; these tiers may be subject to
        operator restrictions, additional contractual terms, and certified
        third-party audits.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight">7. Forward-looking statements</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-crust-300">
        Numbers, dates, and roadmap milestones on this site are targets
        derived from the design dossier and the 24-month plan. They are not
        forecasts and they are not commitments. Decision gates are real; if a
        gate condition is not met, the next phase moves. The foundation
        publishes phase-gate reviews quarterly on the public status page.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- LEGAL-REVIEW-NEEDED — final wording requires counsel sign-off -->
    <div>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight">8. Cookies and analytics</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-crust-300">
        orogen.network does not set tracking cookies, does not load third-party
        analytics scripts (Google Analytics, Segment, Mixpanel, Plausible, or
        equivalents), and does not fingerprint visitors. The only first-party
        state is a session cookie used by the gateway dashboard at
        <code class="rounded bg-crust-800 px-1 py-0.5">gateway.orogen.network</code>
        for authenticated API-key management. Server access logs are
        retained for 14 days for abuse mitigation and rate-limit enforcement,
        then deleted. No browser-side telemetry beacons are emitted from this
        marketing site.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- LEGAL-REVIEW-NEEDED — sanctions-screening provider contracts pending -->
    <div>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight">9. Sanctions screening</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-crust-300">
        The gateway screens customer accounts and operator registration
        applications against the U.S. OFAC SDN list, the EU consolidated
        sanctions list, the UK HMT consolidated list, and the UN consolidated
        list. Wallet-address screening uses two independent providers
        (Chainalysis KYT and TRM Labs, with Elliptic as a tertiary check) to
        avoid single-vendor false positives. Matches are blocked at the
        gateway; the operator's stake is not seized by the protocol absent a
        separate slashing-class fault, but the operator cannot earn rewards
        while blocked. Customers and operators can contest a match by emailing
        <a href="mailto:compliance@orogen.network">compliance@orogen.network</a>.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- LEGAL-REVIEW-NEEDED — retention windows depend on foundation jurisdiction -->
    <div>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight">10. Data retention</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-crust-300">
        Customer prompts and responses are not stored by the protocol after
        the receipt commitment is finalised on-chain. The receipt itself
        contains only content hashes (model_hash, adapter_hash, prompt_hash,
        output_hash), not plaintext. Operators are contractually required to
        purge plaintext from their TEEs at the end of each request lifecycle;
        the TEE attestation chain provides a technical guarantee that plaintext
        does not exit the enclave. Server-side gateway logs containing request
        metadata (timestamps, model identifiers, byte counts, response codes)
        are retained for 30 days for operations and billing reconciliation.
        Receipts and on-chain commitments are permanent by design — they are
        the audit trail. Customers requiring shorter operational-log retention
        for regulatory reasons should contact
        <a href="mailto:enterprise@orogen.network">enterprise@orogen.network</a>.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- LEGAL-REVIEW-NEEDED — non-US disclosure wording depends on local regimes (MiCA, FCA, MAS) -->
    <div>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight">11. Not investment advice (non-US notice)</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-crust-300">
        Nothing on this site constitutes investment advice, financial advice,
        trading advice, or any other form of advice. Information about OROG —
        token mechanics, emission schedule, BME loop dynamics, allocation, and
        roadmap — is provided for informational purposes describing the
        protocol's design. OROG is a utility token used to settle compute work
        on the Orogen network; it is not marketed as a vehicle for capital
        appreciation. You should not buy, hold, or otherwise transact in OROG
        on the basis of an expected return on investment. Tax treatment of
        OROG varies by jurisdiction; consult a qualified professional in your
        jurisdiction before acting. Residents of jurisdictions that restrict
        access to non-bank-issued tokens (including, without limitation,
        certain U.S. retail contexts addressed in §4 above) should not
        attempt to acquire OROG until the geo-fence is lifted for their
        category.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight">12. Trademarks and attribution</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-crust-300">
        Orogen and the Orogen mark are unregistered trademarks of the
        foundation pending registration. NVIDIA, NVTrust, NVL72, H100, H200,
        and B200 are trademarks of NVIDIA Corporation. AMD, Instinct, and
        ROCm are trademarks of Advanced Micro Devices, Inc. Intel TDX is a
        trademark of Intel Corporation. Mentions are nominative and do not
        imply endorsement.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight">13. Contact</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-crust-300">
        General: <a href="mailto:hello@orogen.network">hello@orogen.network</a> · Legal:
        <a href="mailto:legal@orogen.network">legal@orogen.network</a> · Security:
        <a href="mailto:security@orogen.network">security@orogen.network</a> · Enterprise:
        <a href="mailto:enterprise@orogen.network">enterprise@orogen.network</a> · Compliance:
        <a href="mailto:compliance@orogen.network">compliance@orogen.network</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
